The best way to do it is with [Assembly Info][1] Extension, and use the variable `$(Build.BuildNumber)` in the version field.


But if you want to use your own PowerShell script you can do it with this script:

    $buildNumber = &quot;$env:Build_BuildNumber&quot;
    $pattern = &#39;\[assembly: AssemblyVersion\(&quot;(.*)&quot;\)\]&#39;
    $AssemblyFiles = Get-ChildItem . AssemblyInfo.cs -rec
    
    foreach ($file in $AssemblyFiles)
    {
    
    (Get-Content $file.PSPath) | ForEach-Object{
        if($_ -match $pattern){
            &#39;[assembly: AssemblyVersion(&quot;{0}&quot;)]&#39; -f $buildNumber
        } else {
            # Output line as is
            $_
        }
    } | Set-Content $file.PSPath
    
    }


  [1]: https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=bleddynrichards.Assembly-Info-Task

